7.1 Intro of Energy and Work

For work to be done (scientifically), there must be a force exerted on an object in the direction of force.
For there to be work, there has to be a force, and displacement on friction.

  • Work is when I move something while resisting a force
    Equation
Why a ? What's the

The angle between the vectors. The angle between the direction of motion, and the force

7.2 Kinetic Energy and Net work

Work and energy are never wasted. Instead of being wasted, its moved to another form. If we have kinetic energy, it's turned into potential energy or thermal energy. Never wasted

Not on a ramp

The kinetic energy is

Gravity Potential Energy

Work is always done against gravitational force. It's never done with grav force, just against it.

Grav. potential energy applies to any object who has . A rock that never moves up and down, you cant apply GPE.
Gravity's energy only matters where you start and end in terms of location. Not the path you take. Like Session 7 Gravity > ^8a4559Definition 2 (Displacement)!

7.4 Conservative Forces

A conservative force is a force which only relies on the start and end points of motion. Gravity is conservative! Any conservative force that exists, also has a potential energy stored inside of it.

When you pick up a band, you store potential energy in it.
Potential energies are all recoverable as work or kinetic energy.

Presidents are not conservative forces

7.5 More on Conservative Forces

There are either conservative or non conservative.
A nonconservative force, depends on the path it takes!
Conservative forces only need displacement.
Does friction have a potential associated?

  • Nope! You can't get that energy back

These forces take energy away from the system as the system progresses, energy that you can't get back.
Source

Friction creates thermal energy, sliding your hands together makes them fun.
Non-conservative forces either remove or add energy to a system.
Friction makes thermal energy, which then dissipate.
Thermal energy mostly is useless.
Mechanical energy isn't conserved when non-conservative forces are acting

  • Car breaks!

7.6 Law of Conservation of Energy

The total energy is constant in any process, it may move from one to another

U is mechanical energy

Is mechanical energy conserved in any process?

NO! You'll always some non-conservative force acting on the system, making heat.
